'''Hermann Gunkel''' (23 May 1862 – 11 March 1932), a German [[Old Testament]] scholar, founded [[form criticism]].<ref name=biblical>{{cite book | title=Dictionary of Biblical Criticism and Interpretation | chapter=Form Criticism | first=Kenton L. | last=Sparks | pages=111–114 | year=2007 | editor-first=Stanley E | editor-last=Porter | location=New York | publisher=Routledge | chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=EV5x-fX79dQC&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EV5x-fX79dQC}}</ref>  He also became a leading representative of the [[history of religions school]].<ref name=EB>
{{cite web 
| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/249437/Hermann-Gunkel | title=Hermann Gunkel (German biblical scholar) 
| work=Britannica Online Encyclopedia | accessdate=January 2, 2013
}}</ref> His major works cover [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] and the [[Psalms]], and his major interests centered on the oral tradition behind written sources and in folklore.

== Biography ==
Gunkel was born in [[Springe]], [[Kingdom of Hanover]],<ref name=EB /> where his father and grandfather were [[Lutheran]] [[pastor]]s.<ref name=briefhistory>{{cite book | last=Gignilliat | first=Mark S. | title=A Brief History of Old Testament Criticism | year=2012 | publisher=Zondervan | location=Grand Rapids, MI | page=108 | chapter=Hermann Gunkel | chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WrJln5IwiZ8C&pg=PT108}}</ref>  He studied at the [[University of Göttingen]] and the [[University of Giessen]]. He eventually taught at both universities in addition to those of [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin]] and [[University of Halle-Wittenberg|Halle]].<ref name=dictionary>{{cite book | chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFLGroLOKq8C&pg=PA499#v=onepage&q&f=false | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFLGroLOKq8C | editor-last=McKim | editor-first=Donald K | first=M. J. | last=Buss | chapter=Gunkel, Hermann | title=Dictionary of Major Biblical Interpreters | year=2007 | publisher=InterVarsity Press | pages=499–503}}</ref>

Gunkel started his career in [[New Testament]] studies at [[Göttingen]] in 1888. However, he was soon transferred to [[Halle, Saxony-Anhalt|Halle]] (1889-1894) and told to concentrate on the [[Hebrew Bible]] by the Prussian academic appointments authority. He went on to teach in [[Berlin]] (1894-1907), where he made many inter-disciplinary contacts. His 1895 book, ''Creation and Chaos in the Primeval Era and the Eschaton'', compared the symbolism in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] and [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]] 12. In 1901, he produced the first of three editions of commentary on Genesis, ''Genesis Translated and Explained''.<ref name=dictionary />

In 1907, Gunkel finally obtained a full professorship at the [[University of Giessen]]. There he produced the third and final edition of ''Genesis'' in 1910 and ''The Prophets'' in 1917. He moved to the [[University of Halle-Wittenberg]] in 1920. He published another standard work, his commentary on the book of [[Psalms]], ''The Psalms: Translated and Explained'' in 1926. ''Introduction to the Psalms'' was his last major project, brought to completion by his student [[Joachim Begrich]] in 1933.<ref name=dictionary />

Gunkel founded the series ''Research into the Religion and Literature of the Old and New Testaments'' (1903-) with [[Wilhelm Bousset]].<ref name=EB /> He also co-edited with Leopold Zscharnack the second edition of the German religious encyclopedia ''Religion in History and the Present'' (1927-1931), in which he authored over one hundred articles.<ref>{{cite book | title=The Psalms: A Form-Critical Introduction | url=http://www.ericlevy.com/revel/Psalms/Gunkel%20H%20-%20The%20Psalms%20-%20A%20Form-Critical%20Introduction%20Abridged.PDF | first=James | last=Muilenburg | author-link=James Muilenburg|chapter=Introduction | location=Philadelphia | publisher=Fortress Press | year=1967 | page=vii}}</ref>

== Work ==
{{Quote box
|quote = "The influence of the methods pioneered by Gunkel upon subsequent Old Testament study can scarcely be overestimated."
|source = [[Ernest Nicholson]], “Foreword: Hermann Gunkel as a Pioneer of Modern Old Testament Study,” in Hermann Gunkel, ''Genesis'' (trans. Mark E. Biddle; Macon, GA: Mercer University Press, 1997), 9.
|width = 25%
}}

Gunkel became a leading representative of the "[[history of religions school]]" (''Religionsgeschichtliche Schule''), which addressed the history of traditions behind the biblical text. In addition to Gunkel, the original group also included [[Albert Eichhorn]], [[William Wrede]], Heinrich Hackmann, [[Alfred Rahlfs]], [[Johannes Weiss]], [[Wilhelm Bousset]], [[Ernst Troeltsch]], and [[Wilhelm Heitmüller]].<ref name=ludemann>
{{cite journal|last=Lüdemann|first=Gerd|authorlink=Gerd Ludemann|title=The Relationship of Biblical Studies to the History of Religions School, with Reference to the Scientific Study of Religion| journal=[[Toronto Journal of Theology]] |year=2008 |volume=24|issue=2|page= 173 |url = http://wwwuser.gwdg.de/%7Egluedem/download/02_tjt24.2_ludemann.pdf |doi=10.3138/tjt.24.2.171}}
</ref> Gunkel and the school thought that the oral traditions that form the origins of the Hebrew Bible were directly tied to other Near Eastern religions.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lundström |first=Steven |editor1-last=Scurlock |editor1-first=JoAnn |editor2-last=Beal |editor2-first=Richard H. |
chapter=Chaos and Creation: Hermann Gunkel between Establishing the "History of Religions School," Acknowledging Assyriology,and Defending the Faith |title= Creation and Chaos: A Reconsideration of Hermann Gunkel’s Chaoskampf Hypothesis |publisher=Eisenbrauns |date=2013 |pages=147–171 |chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/2441988/Chaos_and_Creation._Hermann_Gunkel_between_Establishing_the_History_of_Religions_School_Acknowledging_Assyriology_and_Defending_the_Faith_in_J._Scurlock_ed._Creation_and_Chaos_A_Reconsideration_of_Hermann_Gunkel_s_Chaos_Kampf_Hypothesis_Winona_Lake_in_press_ }}</ref>
Gunkel arguably produced his most important work in his commentary on [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]], published in three editions from 1901 to 1910.<ref>
{{cite journal|last=Mihelic|first=Joseph|title=The Influence of Form Criticism on the Study of the Old Testament|journal=Journal of the American Academy of Religion|year=1951|volume=XIX|issue=3|pages=120–129|doi=10.1093/jaarel/XIX.3.120|url=http://jaar.oxfordjournals.org/content/XIX/3/120.extract}}
</ref>  In these works he created the new critical methodology of [[form criticism]] (''Formgeschichte'').<ref>
{{cite journal|last=Muilenburg|first=James| author-link=James Muilenburg|title=Form Criticism and beyond|journal=Journal of Biblical Literature|date=March 1969|volume=88|issue=1|pages=1–18|jstor=3262829|doi=10.2307/3262829}}
</ref>  Form criticism examined the genres used in the biblical text to identify the ''[[Sitz im Leben]]'' (setting in life) that produced the text. This approach was based on the assumption that each genre is organically associated with a particular social and historical situation. Nineteenth-century [[source criticism]] had examined the biblical text, especially the [[Pentateuch]], on the basis of style, vocabulary, theology, and other criteria to identify the basic literary sources used to create the text. Form criticism allowed scholars to go behind these larger literary sources by identifying the smaller and older sources used by their authors.<ref>{{cite web |title=Form Criticism |url=http://www.oxfordbiblicalstudies.com/article/opr/t94/e693 |work=Oxford Biblical Studies Online}}</ref> Because of its utility, form criticism became immensely influential in Germany and Europe during the 20th century, with important scholars like [[Gerhard von Rad]] and [[Martin Noth]] applying and developing it.{{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}

